In a press conference on February 16, 2017, Trump said that when white House Counsel Don McGahn first told him acting AG Yates' account of Flynn's calls, he believed that nothing was wrong with them. But according to Yates' testimony, on Jan 26, Yates informed McGahn that Flynn had been interviewed by the FBI, explained Flynn's conduct in detail and told McGahn that not only did Flynn lie about the calls to the Vice President, but that the calls were problematic in and of themselves. The next day, McGahn called Yates to ask about the "applicability of certain criminal statutes," ask if taking action would interfere with any investigation of Flynn, and request to see the underlying evidence of Flynn's conduct. These actions aren't characteristic of someone who believed "nothing was wrong."

In that same press conference, Trump cited reading "various articles" as why he thought nothing was wrong with Flynn's calls:


