But in the days leading up to Yates' warning to the White House, there were multiple conflicting articles on the calls, some saying that investigators found nothing wrong and others saying the investigation was ongoing. Washington Post appears to have be the source for the articles claiming investigators found nothing illicit. Yet Trump chose to believe Washington Post's version of events over the Wall Street Journal's, despite his disdain for Washington Post (e.g. http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-revokes-washington-post-s-press-credentials-n591586) and his belief that the "financial media" are "much more honest."

By all indications, Trump knew that Flynn's calls with the Russian ambassador were under investigation and that there was a possibility investigators would find wrongdoing. Yet Trump made public statements claiming he believed nothing was wrong, citing reasons that don't hold up to scrutiny.

In fact, the President has shown intent to conceal Flynn's misconduct. President Trump said he knew Flynn "didn't tell the vice president properly the facts:"
 
